exp:Experiment.exp:Name: Lung Adenocarcinoma Study
exp:Experiment.exp:Hypothesis: Whole protein fractionation can be used to identify protiens in a biosample existing in two forms.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Lung Adenocarcinoma Profile
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Profiling of Proteins in Lung Adenocarcinoma Cell Surface

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Biotinylation
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Each cell dish was biotinylated with 10mL of Sulpho-NHS-LC-biotin 0.25mg/mL in D-PBS. The reaction was carried out at room temperature (23-24C) for 10 min. The biotinylation solution was drained and the residual biotinylation reagent was quenched with 10mM Lysine, in DMEM media (without addition of serum or antibiotics) for 5 minutes at room temperature. The quenching solution was drained and the cells were washed twice with 10mL of D-PBS.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Protein Extraction
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Proteins were extracted by scraping the cell dishes in 1mL of NP 40 detergent solution (2%v/v) in D-PBS, containing 1 tablet of protease inhibitor per each 7mL of extraction solution. Solution was kept in ice all the time. Cells were further disrupted by three cycles of 30 sonication pulses (duty cycle 30, output 4, Branson Sonifier – VWR Scientific) and 1 min. in ice bath.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Protein Purification
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Extraction solution was clarified by centrifugation at 20000 x g (Beckman) for 30min at 4ºC.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: SDS-PAGE Western Blotting
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Eluted proteins were concentrated in iCON devices (9kDa cut-off) and separated by SDS-PAGE. Samples were diluted in SDS sample buffer containing 75mM DTT, reduced for 5 min at 100ºC, alkylated for 30 minutes at room temperature in the dark with addition iodoacetamide to final concentration of 100mM and run in a pre-cast Ready Gel (8.6 x 6.8 cm, 12%) using Tris-glycine buffer system. Gels were stained with Gel Code blue solution. A duplicate gel was electroblotted to PVDF to visualize biotinylated proteins. Membranes were blocked for 1 hour with 5% non fat dry milk in PBST (0.1% tween 20 in D-PBS), washed and incubated for 1 hour with HRP-streptavidin conjugate (at 1:1500 dilution) in PBST. After three washes with PBST, the membrane was incubate with ECL reagents and exposed to Hyperfilm ECL.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Slice Gel Lanes by Intervals
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Two lanes loaded with 20µg of biotynilated proteins were divided in 28 pieces of 2.5mm each and submitted to in-situ digestion. Gel pieces were washed 5 times with ammonium bicarbonate 50mM / acetonitrile 50% to remove SDS and coomassie, dehydrated with 100% acetonitrile and dried for 30 min in speedvac. Digestion was performed with addition of 20µL of ammonium bicarbonate 100mM containing 100ng of trypsin and carried out overnight at 37ºC. Peptides were extracted with 10µL of 2% formic acid.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Do MS2 Scans
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Peptides were analyzed by LC-MS/MS in an LTQ-FTICR mass spectrometer using data-dependent acquisition. The acquisition method consisted of cycles of one FT MS scan acquired at resolution of 50000 for the range 400-2000Da, then selection of the three most abundant ions for MS/MS analysis in the linear ion trap using collision energy of 35%. Ions previously selected for MS/MS were dynamically excluded for 30 seconds.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Convert to mzXML
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: Raw ThermoFinnigan file was converted to an mzXML file using ReAdW.exe program from the Sashimi open source project.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: XTandem analysis
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: X!Tandem was used to find the best peptide sequence match for each MS2 spectra and to generate all statistics (e.g., expectation score, missed cleavages) associated with the matches.

exp:Protocol.exp:Name: Convert To PepXml
exp:Protocol.exp:ProtocolDescription: X!Tandem native output was converted to pepXML standard using Tandem2XML program from the Sashimi Trans-Proteomic Pipeline open source project.
